<h4>1.1 Introduction of Numbers</h4>
<div class="fun-box">
Numbers are fundamental mathematical objects used for counting, measuring, and labeling.  
Natural numbers are denoted by <strong>N</strong>.
</div>

<h5>Set Comparison:</h5>
<p>
All natural numbers are whole numbers, but 0 is a whole number and not a natural number.
</p>

<h5>Properties of Natural Numbers</h5>

<p><strong>Closure under addition and multiplication:</strong><br>
2 + 3 = 5<br>
2 × 3 = 6
</p>

<p><strong>Not closed under subtraction:</strong><br>
2 − 5 = −3
</p>

<p><strong>Not closed under division:</strong><br>
5 ÷ 2 = 2.5
</p>

<p><strong>Examples:</strong><br>
Counting: You have 3 potatoes.<br>
Ordering: It is the 5th clever student.<br>
Labeling: The jersey number is 10.
</p>

<h5>Review Questions</h5>
<p>
1. Which one of the following is a natural number?<br>
A. −4 &nbsp; B. ⅚ &nbsp; C. 0 &nbsp; D. 3<br><br>

2. Add 3 + 4. Answer: ____<br><br>

3. Smallest natural number: ____<br><br>

4. Largest natural number: ____<br><br>

5. Multiply 5 × 6: ____<br>
</p>

<h4>1.3 Whole Numbers</h4>
<p>
Whole numbers are natural numbers plus zero.  
Examples: 0, 1, 2, 3, …
</p>

<p><strong>Relationship to Other Sets:</strong><br>
Natural Numbers: {1,2,3,...}<br>
Integers: {...,−2,−1,0,1,2,...}<br>
Smallest Whole Number: 0
</p>

<h5>Operations on Whole Numbers</h5>

<p><strong>Addition:</strong><br>
Closed under addition. Example: 5 + 3 = 8
</p>

<p><strong>Subtraction:</strong><br>
Not closed. Example: 3 − 5 = −2
</p>

<p><strong>Multiplication:</strong><br>
Closed under multiplication.
</p>

<p><strong>Division:</strong><br>
Not closed. 7 ÷ 2 = 3.5
</p>

<h5>Review Questions</h5>
<p>
1. Define the set of whole numbers.<br><br>
2. Difference between whole and natural numbers?<br><br>
3. Is −5 whole? Why?<br><br>
4. Identify property: 2 × (5 + 3) = (2 × 5) + (2 × 3)<br><br>
5. Simplify: (a + 0) × (b × 1) × 0<br>
</p>

<h4>1.4 Rational Numbers</h4>
<p>
A rational number is written as p/q where q ≠ 0.
</p>

<h5>Examples:</h5>
<p>
5 = 5/1<br>
−3 = −3/1<br>
0 = 0/1
</p>

<h4>1.5 Basic Operations on Rational Numbers</h4>

<h5>Addition and Subtraction</h5>
<p>
Compute: 6/1 + 3/2<br>
Compute: −8/7 − 4/1
</p>

<h5>Multiplication and Division</h5>
<p>
Compute: (9/5) × (−10/3)<br>
Compute: −10/9 ÷ 5/3
</p>

<h5>Order of Operations</h5>
<p>
Compute: 3/1 × (4/3 + 4/1)
</p>

<h5>Review Questions</h5>
<p>
1. Compute: −5/3 + 2/1<br>
2. Find: 10/7 − (−5/1)<br>
3. Compute: (−2) × 9/4<br>
4. Compute: 14 1/7 ÷ 8 5/7<br>
</p>

